–1510","1408–1470":"1408–1470","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1408":"1408","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Perkes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Parkes   or   Parkhouse  .","Jewish (from Ukraine): metronymic from the Yiddish name <i>Perke</i> (a pet form of the female personal name <i>Perl</i> ‘pearl’; see   Perel   2) + the Yiddish possessive suffix <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Parkes","meanings":["English: variant of   Parks  ."]}]},{"name":"Havens","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Haven  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Welsh: variant of   Evans  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heavens","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Havens  ."]},{"name":"Haven","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) harbor’, from Middle English <i>haven</i> (Old English <i>hæfen</i> ‘haven’).","Welsh (Monmouthshire): variant of   Evan  .","Dutch: variant of   Haveman  , or possibly a topographic name from <i>haven</i> ‘port, harbour’. See also   De Haven  ."]},{"name":"Havins","meanings":["English: variant of   Havens  .","Welsh: variant of   Evans  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Mary Perkes Havens was born in 1420, in Buckinghamshire, England, her father, John Perkes, was 20 and her mother, Mary Williams, was 21. She had at least 1 daughter with Richard Moore. She died in 1510, in her hometown, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1420–1510":"1420–1510","1408–1470":"1408–1470","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1408":"1408","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1420–1510":"1420–1510","1408–1470":"1408–1470","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1460":"1460